# .cursorrules — Jinesh / Stalwart Learning training repos
# Standing guardrails for ALL hands-on lab code (Azure ETL, Palantir Foundry, etc.)
# Cursor MUST obey every rule below on every task in this repo.
# Drop this file in the repo root. Cursor loads it automatically every session.
# (Newer Cursor: same content can live at .cursor/rules/guardrails.mdc)
# Last updated: 2026-06-23

## 0. WORKING METHOD — plan before you touch anything (NO ad-hoc edits)
- NEVER edit, create, or run anything ad-hoc. Always output a PLAN first, then execute it:
  1. Restate the goal in one line.
  2. A table of every file you will create/change, with a one-line reason for each.
  3. The scripts you will run, and the single re-run command that proves it works.
  4. Which guardrail (sections below) each change satisfies.
- Execute the plan top-to-bottom. No surprises mid-way, no improvising.
- If a change does not trace to a guardrail or an explicit instruction, DO NOT make it.
- Prefer the smallest change that satisfies the guardrail. Less code = fewer mistakes.

## 1. PLATFORM — Windows, from scratch, exactly ONE entry point
- Target OS is Windows ONLY. Never write or depend on .sh, bash, zsh, or any macOS tooling.
- Every project exposes exactly ONE entry point: `orchestrate.cmd`.
  - It must run on a CLEAN Windows machine where ONLY Windows (and at most Python) exists.
  - It bootstraps everything else itself: installs/locates Azure CLI, creates the venv,
    pip-installs requirements, scaffolds `.env` from `.env.example` if missing.
  - The learner must NOT have to change PowerShell execution policy by hand, run as admin
    unnecessarily, or pre-activate a venv.
- If logic must live in PowerShell, call it from `orchestrate.cmd` via
  `powershell -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File ...` so the learner never touches policy.
- Real logic lives in Python (orchestrate.py). The .cmd is a thin, dumb launcher only.
- Acceptance test: "A learner with a brand-new laptop runs ONE command and gets a working
  lab." If that isn't true, the task is NOT done.

## 2. IDEMPOTENCY — safe to re-run, every time, every scenario
- There is always ONE re-run command. Running it 1 or 10 times gives the SAME end state:
  no duplicate resources, no crash, no manual cleanup.
- Enforce idempotency by construction, not by hoping:
  - Deterministic resource names (Bicep `uniqueString(LEARNER...)`), never random per run.
  - ARM/Bicep INCREMENTAL deployments — update in place, never duplicate.
  - Check-before-create for everything the CLI does (RBAC, role assignments, workspaces):
    if it already exists, log "already present" and skip — do not error.
- Before declaring done, walk these four re-run scenarios and confirm each is safe:
  - Fresh machine, nothing deployed yet.
  - Re-run after a full success.
  - Re-run after a partial / failed run (resume, do not double-create).
  - Re-run after teardown.
- Document the exact re-run command AND these four scenarios in the README.

## 3. README — teach the concept first, THEN the code, line by line
The README is for a learner who has never seen this stack. Structure EVERY README as:
  A. WHAT & WHY per component, plain language + one analogy, BEFORE any code.
     e.g. "Bicep is the blueprint for your Azure house. Why: the whole environment is
     declared in one file and rebuilt identically every time, instead of clicking in the
     portal." Cover every component the lab uses (Bicep, Resource Group, Key Vault,
     ADLS Gen2, Data Factory, Databricks, Purview, Budget, RBAC...).
  B. "Now go to the code" — point to the exact file for each component.
  C. The code itself is commented line-by-line / block-by-block: every non-trivial line says
     WHAT it does and WHY it's there. A learner understands the file by reading top to bottom.
- README also contains: one-command quick start, the re-run command, the teardown command,
  and the four re-run scenarios from section 2.

## 4. DOCS-AS-CODE — nothing stays only on the local machine
- Every behaviour change updates its documentation IN THE SAME CHANGE:
  README.md, docs/TRAINER-NOTES.md, and any affected guide.
- All edits go through committed files — never tell the learner to "just change it locally".
- If you change a flag, a resource, a region, or a step, the docs reflect it before commit.
- The git repo is the single source of truth. If it isn't in git, it doesn't exist.

## 5. VERSION CONTROL — trunk-based, commit to main, push ALL remotes
- Commit directly to `main`. Small, frequent, working commits — no long-lived branches.
- After completing a task (code + docs + tested re-run), ALWAYS:
  `git add -A`  →  `git commit -m "<clear message + guardrail>"`  →  `git push origin main`
  and push to every other configured remote (e.g. `class`).
- Never leave a task with uncommitted changes. A broken main is the top-priority fix.

## 6. COST & REGION GUARDRAILS — the bracketed rules, always remembered
- Region: UK only — `uksouth` primary, `ukwest` failover. Any non-UK region (e.g. Purview in
  eastus) must be an EXPLICIT, documented exception with a one-line reason.
- SKUs: cheapest viable tier only. Enforce with `verify_cost.py` SKU allow-list.
- Spend: minimum / minimal philosophy. Keep the budget resource + MTD cost gate. A run that would
  cost money must WARN, not silently proceed.
- MPN limits: where a service is blocked (Synapse provisioning, Fabric quota 0), skip cleanly
  with a documented manual workaround — never hard-fail the whole lab.
- These guardrails apply to EVERY piece of code in this repo, always.

## 7. DONE = verified AND validated (Artem V&V)
- Verification ("did we build it right?"): the script runs, deploys the expected resources,
  verify_cost passes, the re-run is clean.
- Validation ("did we build the RIGHT thing?"): a fresh learner on a clean Windows box, using
  ONLY the README, reaches a working lab with one command AND understands each piece.
- A task is done only when BOTH hold. State both explicitly when you finish.

## PER-PROJECT OVERRIDES (edit these lines, not the rules above)
- LEARNER / subscription : <set per engagement>
- Region primary/failover: uksouth / ukwest
- Single entry point     : orchestrate.cmd
- Git remotes            : origin, class
